+{"file":"src/observability/task_inspector.rs","lines":1246,"batch":417,"date":"2026-03-20","agent":"GrayCastle","verdict":"FIXED","bugs":2,"notes":"Fresh-eyes audit found two concrete correctness issues. First, TaskInspector measured task age and snapshot time from timer_driver().now() even though task timestamps are recorded against RuntimeState::now, so runtimes without a timer driver collapsed stuck-task age to zero; the inspector now uses the runtime logical clock with a regression covering age, stuck_count, and generated_at. Second, inspect_task() reported every obligation whose holder matched the task, including committed entries still retained in the table; it now uses the pending-holder index so only live obligations are reported, with a focused regression for committed-vs-pending visibility."}
+{"file":"src/combinator/circuit_breaker.rs","lines":2090,"batch":418,"date":"2026-03-20","agent":"WindyBear","verdict":"FIXED","bugs":2,"notes":"Fresh-eyes follow-up on recent half-open sliding-window changes found two remaining issues: a stale regression still encoded the wrong model (it assumed close-time reset, rather than open-time reset, was responsible for clearing stale failures), and the live HalfOpen->Closed success path still performed that close-time sliding-window reset. The regression now asserts the real invariant and the runtime path preserves successful probe history after recovery."}
+{"file":"src/messaging/redis.rs","lines":2301,"batch":420,"date":"2026-03-21","agent":"SageHawk","verdict":"FIXED","bugs":1,"notes":"Deep audit of Redis pubsub flow found a real reliability bug: RedisPubSub::ping() consumed and discarded interleaved Message/Subscription events while waiting for PONG, so liveness probes could lose real pubsub traffic. Fixed by adding a pending_events queue, routing next_event() through it, and buffering ping interleavings instead of dropping them; added a focused socket-level regression."}
+{"file":"src/observability/task_inspector.rs","lines":1271,"batch":419,"date":"2026-03-20","agent":"GrayCastle","verdict":"FIXED","bugs":1,"notes":"Fresh-eyes follow-up on the earlier TaskInspector audit found the clock-source fix had over-corrected toward `RuntimeState::now`. Live runtimes advance observability time through the timer driver while `state.now` is primarily maintained in timerless/lab paths, so always reading `state.now` could underreport task age and snapshot time. `current_time()` now prefers `timer_driver().now()` when available and falls back to `state.now` only when no timer driver exists, with a mixed-mode regression proving timer-driver preference and timerless fallback."}
+{"file":"src/lab/explorer.rs","lines":0,"batch":419,"date":"2026-03-20","agent":"CobaltGate","verdict":"FIXED","bugs":2,"notes":"Fresh-eyes diff audit of the active explorer surface found two concrete queue-management bugs. First, DporExplorer and TopologyExplorer only deduplicated against explored seeds, so the same derived seed could be queued multiple times before first execution; both now track pending seeds to keep the work queue/frontier unique. Second, both explore loops popped one extra seed before enforcing max_runs, which silently dropped the next unexplored seed from report.top_unexplored; the run-budget guard now fires before popping, with focused regressions for both explorers."}
+{"file":"src/service/load_balance.rs","lines":1867,"batch":421,"date":"2026-03-20","agent":"BlueHeron","verdict":"FIXED","bugs":2,"notes":"Random deep archaeology through service load balancing and discovery found constructor-time topology reconciliation drift in the weighted strategy. First, LoadBalancer::empty() never called Strategy::sync_backend_count, so strategies with pre-seeded topology metadata started out inconsistent with an actually empty backend set. Second, Weighted::sync_backend_count only grew vectors instead of reconciling them exactly to the live backend count, leaving phantom weight/current_weight slots after constructor initialization with fewer backends than weights. Empty/new now force exact alignment, with focused regressions for empty weighted balancers and shrinking pre-seeded weighted state to the actual backend count."}
+{"file":"src/messaging/redis.rs","lines":2433,"batch":422,"date":"2026-03-20","agent":"BlueHeron","verdict":"FIXED","bugs":1,"notes":"Peer-review audit of the recent pubsub ping buffering change found a reconnect isolation bug: ping() now preserves interleaved events in pending_events, but reconnect() replaced the underlying connection and restored subscriptions without clearing that buffer, so next_event() could return stale pre-reconnect messages from the dead session before reading the new socket. reconnect() now drops buffered events when swapping sessions, with a focused regression proving reconnect only exposes fresh post-reconnect traffic."}
+{"file":"src/trace/dpor.rs","lines":830,"batch":422,"date":"2026-03-20","agent":"SageHawk","verdict":"FIXED","bugs":1,"notes":"Peer-review of the DPOR explorer path found the sleep-set deduplication key was too coarse: SleepSet::bp_key() hashed only divergence/index shape plus event-kind discriminants, so two different races with the same structural shape could alias and cause unsound cross-trace pruning. Fixed by hashing the semantic trace_event_key() of both race endpoints instead, and added a regression proving same-shape races on different tasks no longer collide."}
+{"file":"src/trace/dpor.rs","lines":867,"batch":423,"date":"2026-03-20","agent":"HazyCrane","verdict":"FIXED","bugs":1,"notes":"Fresh-eyes follow-up on the new sleep-set semantic-key hardening found the backtrack-point key was still directional. After exploring one ordering of a dependent race, the same race encountered in reverse endpoint order produced a different key and could be redundantly re-enqueued. SleepSet::bp_key() now normalizes the two semantic endpoint keys before hashing, with a regression proving reverse-order traces deduplicate while different-task same-shape races remain distinct."}
+{"file":"src/process.rs","lines":2464,"batch":424,"date":"2026-03-20","agent":"HazyCrane","verdict":"FIXED","bugs":1,"notes":"Peer-review of the recent kill_on_drop reaper change found the runtime-thread detection heuristic was too narrow. should_background_reap_kill_on_drop() only checked Cx::current(), but runtime worker threads keep Runtime::current_handle() installed even when no task is actively being polled, so dropping a Child on a worker outside task-poll context could still take the blocking wait path and stall the worker. The guard now treats either an ambient Cx or an installed runtime handle as reason to offload the reap, with a regression covering worker-thread startup before the first task poll."}
+{"file":"src/service/load_balance.rs","lines":1921,"batch":425,"date":"2026-03-20","agent":"GreenBrook","verdict":"FIXED","bugs":1,"notes":"Peer-review of the recent weighted-topology reconciliation change found a configuration-loss regression: `LoadBalancer::empty()` now called `sync_backend_count(0)` and `Weighted::sync_backend_count()` shrank the weights vector to the live backend count, so caller-supplied deferred weights were silently discarded for empty or partially materialized balancers. `Weighted` now tracks live backend count separately from the configured weight plan, preserving deferred weights for later insertions while keeping live SWRR state aligned with actual backends; added focused regressions for empty and partial-constructor activation."}
